---
import PostLayout from '../../layouts/PostLayout.astro';

const faqSchema = [
  {
    question: 'What law governs fire safety regulations for businesses in the UK?',
    answer:
      'The primary legislation is the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 (RRO), which applies to all non-domestic premises in England and Wales. It places legal duties on the "responsible person" — typically the employer, owner, or managing agent — to carry out fire risk assessments and implement appropriate fire-safety measures.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why are blocked fire exits a fire safety violation?',
    answer:
      'Under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005, fire exits and escape routes must be kept clear and unobstructed at all times. Blocked exits prevent occupants from evacuating safely and can result in enforcement action, fines, or prosecution.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How many fire extinguishers does a business need?',
    answer:
      'As a general rule, buildings require at least one fire extinguisher per 200 square metres of floor space, with a minimum of two per floor. The types of extinguisher required depend on the fire risks present. A fire risk assessment will specify the correct number and type for your premises.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What fire safety equipment is legally required for businesses?',
    answer:
      'Legally required fire safety equipment varies by building type and risk level, but commonly includes fire extinguishers of appropriate types, fire blankets (in kitchens), fire alarm systems, emergency lighting, and fire-safety signage. All equipment must be correctly positioned, maintained, and regularly serviced.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How often should fire alarms be tested?',
    answer:
      'Fire alarms should be tested at least weekly by activating a different call point each week, with a full annual inspection and service by a competent person. Records of all tests and maintenance must be kept.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is a fire risk assessment a legal requirement for businesses?',
    answer:
      'Yes. The Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 requires the responsible person of any non-domestic premises to carry out — or commission — a suitable and sufficient fire risk assessment, keep a written record (for premises with five or more employees), and review it regularly or whenever significant changes occur.',
  },
];
---

<PostLayout
  title="5 Common Fire Safety Regulations Broken by Businesses"
  description="Many UK businesses unknowingly violate the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005. From blocked exits to absent risk assessments, here are the five most common breaches — and how to avoid them."
  publishDate="2022-11-25"
  updateDate="2023-11-24"
  author="Liam Bee"
  category="Fire Safety Regulations"
  slug="5-common-fire-safety-regulations-broken-by-businesses"
  readTime="4 min read"
  faqSchema={faqSchema}
>
  <p>
    Fire safety legislation exists to protect lives — yet many UK businesses unknowingly breach the
    <strong>Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005</strong> (RRO), putting occupants at risk and
    exposing themselves to enforcement action, fines, and prosecution. Here are the five most common
    fire safety violations found in business premises, and what you can do to avoid them.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Blocked or Obstructed Fire Exits</h2>

  <p>
    Fire exits and escape routes must be kept clear and accessible at all times. This is one of the
    most frequently cited violations during fire safety inspections. Common causes include:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Stock, equipment, or furniture left in corridors and stairwells</li>
    <li>Fire doors wedged open or propped with objects</li>
    <li>Emergency exit doors that are locked or require a key to open from the inside</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Under the RRO, escape routes must be kept clear, adequately lit, and signed. Review your escape
    routes regularly and ensure all staff know not to obstruct them.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Missing or Inadequate Fire Extinguishers</h2>

  <p>
    Many businesses either have no fire extinguishers, have too few for the size of their premises,
    or have the wrong type for the fire risks present. The general rule is at least one extinguisher
    per 200 square metres, with a minimum of two per floor — but the correct specification depends
    on your fire risk assessment.
  </p>

  <p>
    Fire extinguishers must also be serviced annually by a competent person. Extinguishers that have
    not been serviced, have damaged seals, or are past their service date do not meet legal
    requirements.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Incorrect or Poorly Maintained Fire Safety Equipment</h2>

  <p>
    Having fire safety equipment is not enough — it must be the right equipment for the risks in
    your premises, correctly positioned, and properly maintained. Common failures include:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Water extinguishers used in areas with electrical equipment (where CO₂ is required)</li>
    <li>Fire blankets absent from kitchen areas</li>
    <li>Emergency lighting that has not been tested or is not functioning</li>
    <li>Fire-safety signage that is missing, faded, or obscured</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Your fire risk assessment should specify the correct type and placement of all fire safety
    equipment. A competent fire safety provider can audit your equipment against your specific risks.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Faulty or Untested Fire Alarms</h2>

  <p>
    Fire alarms save lives — but only if they work. Businesses are required to test their fire alarm
    system at least weekly (activating a different call point each week) and have the full system
    inspected and serviced by a competent person at least annually.
  </p>

  <p>
    Common violations include:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>No formal testing schedule in place</li>
    <li>Call points or detectors that are not functioning</li>
    <li>No written records of alarm tests and maintenance</li>
    <li>Alarm systems that are outdated and no longer appropriate for the building's use or occupancy</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Keep a logbook of all alarm tests, faults, and servicing. This documentation will be requested
    during any fire safety inspection.
  </p>

  <h2>5. No Fire Risk Assessment</h2>

  <p>
    The most fundamental requirement under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 is the
    fire risk assessment — and yet many businesses either have never conducted one, or have an
    out-of-date assessment that no longer reflects the current state of their premises.
  </p>

  <p>
    The RRO requires the responsible person to:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Carry out a suitable and sufficient fire risk assessment of the premises</li>
    <li>Keep a written record of the assessment (mandatory for premises with five or more employees)</li>
    <li>Act on the findings and implement appropriate fire-safety measures</li>
    <li>Review the assessment regularly, and whenever significant changes occur (change of use, building work, new hazards, etc.)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Failure to have a fire risk assessment in place is a criminal offence. If your assessment is
    missing or out of date, commissioning a professional fire risk assessment is the single most
    important step you can take to protect your building and comply with the law.
  </p>

